@node "Support?" "Support?"
@prev "Greetings"
@next "Editcomfort"

Soooo, there's a new tool and you want to know if it's supported....
Well, here are some facts:

you can edit your descriptions with the well known "DIZ-Ed" by nocTurne
deSign/OGN and then just treat the file as a TEXT file and everything will
work fine! The same with loading the description from an xpk-file!

xfdDecrunch by Georg Hörmann doesn't YET (I will discuss this issue with
him) extract the description, but normal unpacking works fine (as with the
xpk-package itself). If you don't want to lose the description, just make
a little script that extracts the description, then decrunch the xpk-file.

-Addition: Scripts (AmigaDOS/DOpus) are already present in archive!
           So there's almost no need for DIZ-Ed or an implementation in xfd!
@endnode

@node "Editcomfort" "Editcomfort"
@prev "Support?"
@next "Commandline"

 Do you want more comfort at diz-editing??? here it is!!!

Here's a little script to use with DOpus which makes it more comfortable
for you to view/add/edit a diz so there is NO MORE excuse, believe me!



---- View xDiz-Button {DOpus, No Filename Quote: ON}

  AmigaDOS    xDiz {f} v


---- Edit xDiz-Button {DOpus, No Filename Quote: ON}

  AmigaDOS    copy "c:xDiz.Mask" "t:{ou}"           edit empty diz to add
 *AmigaDOS    copy "c:xDiz.Mask-Temporary" "t:{ou}"
  AmigaDOS    xDiz "{fu}" x "t:{ou}"                if file was already
                                                    xDizzed, EDIT this diz!
 +AmigaDOS    ed "t:{ou}"                           edit diz
  AmigaDOS    xDiz "{fu}" a "t:{ou}"                add diz to xpk file
  AmigaDOS    delete "t:{o}"                        delete diz file

 *: for temporary usage, when you have to describe more files that are
    somehow similar (e.g. 10 files from the same musicdisk etc.), just
    delete this fiel afterwards and and the xDiz.Mask will be used again!

 +: make sure that the editor doesn't return immediatly, but waites until
    you finish editing, otherwise the opus-script would continue without
    the edited diz, so nothing would be changed... use e.g. golded or con-
    figure your ced if possible (i'm to lazy to try!).



The same for NON-DOpus users.. It's a DOS script!

---- View xDiz-Script {AmigaDOS-no sense for this one!?!}

.key xpkFile/a
xDiz "<xpkFile>" v


---- Edit xDiz-Script {AmigaDOS}

.key xpkFile/a
failat 27
copy c:xDiz.Mask "t:cALL tHE aMBUSH-aBYSS wHQ!"       ;edit empty diz to add
copy c:xDiz.Mask-Temporary "t:cALL tHE aMBUSH-aBYSS wHQ!" >NIL:  ;*
xDiz "<xpkFile>" x "t:cALL tHE aMBUSH-aBYSS wHQ!"     ;if file was already
                                                      ;xDizzed, EDIT this diz!
ed "t:cALL tHE aMBUSH-aBYSS wHQ!"                     ;+  edit diz
xDiz "<xpkFile>" a "t:cALL tHE aMBUSH-aBYSS wHQ!"     ;add diz to xpk file
delete "t:cALL tHE aMBUSH-aBYSS wHQ!" >NIL:           ;delete diz file

 */+: same as above!

;-) copy the xDiz.Mask file to your c: directory!



Here we go with some xfdDecrunch-Scripts!

---- xfdDecrunch-Script {DOpus, this one decrunches to the destination dir,
                         No Filename Quote: ON}

  AmigaDOS    xDiz "{fu}" x "{d}{ou}.xDiz"
  AmigaDOS    xfdDecrunch "{f}" "{d}"


---- xfdDecrunch-Script {AmigaDOS, also to destination dir}

.key xpkFile/a,DestDir/a
xDiz "<xpkFile>" x "<xpkFile>.xDiz"
copy "<xpkFile>.xDiz" "<DestDir>"
delete "<xpkFile>.xDiz"
xfdDecrunch "<xpkFile>" "<DestDir>"



Now some xpk-Packing-Script {Also in use with xfdDecrunch-Script!,
                             No Filename Quote: ON}

---- Pack xpkSQSH {DOpus}

  AmigaDOS    xpk -m SQSH "{fu}"       
  AmigaDOS    xDiz "{fu}" a "{ou}.xDiz"
  AmigaDOS    delete "{o}.xDiz"


---- Pack xpkSQSH {AmigaDOS}

.key xpkFile/a
xpk -m SQSH "<xpkFile>"
xDiz "<xpkFile>" a "<xpkFile>.xDiz"
delete "<xpkFile>.xDiz"
@endnode

@node "Commandline" "Commandline"
@prev "Editcomfort"
@next "Standard"

 The Commandline Parameters:

ReadArgs Template:
  xpkFile/A,X=ExtractDizTo/K,S=StripDiz/S,A=AddDizFrom/K,V=ViewDiz/S,
  I=IgnoreLines/M:

  xpkFile:     The xpk-packed file

  X dizfile:   Extract Diz from xpkFile to DiZFiLE

  S:           Strip Diz from xpkFile

  A dizfile:   Add Diz from DiZFiLE to xpkFile
               (old Diz will ofcourse be stripped first)

  V:           View Diz from xpkFile

  I par1 par2: Ignore lines from Diz that start with e.g. par1 or par2
               (only in use with X or V)

Example: xDiz MOD.GlobalConfusion.XPK V
         xDiz MOD.GlobalConfusion.XPK X T:GlobalConfDizOld A HD1:DizNew

         xDiz UploadedFile X t:FILE_ID.DIZ I filetype realsize (c)

------> a MUST for BSSs, because otherwise the filelisting would be TOOO
        long... but this doesn't mean that you shouldn't write this
        lines into the diz, the information just shouldn't be extracted,
        but the information should still be there!!!
@endnode

@node "Standard" "Standard!"
@prev "Commandline"
@next "FutureVersions"

Yeeez, a new standard is born... as I hate filelistings where every single
file_id looks different and you don't have any REAL overview over all the
files (modules in my case!), I designed a form that you just have to load
in DIZ-Ed (or into any other editor, see also "Edit Comfort"), fill in the
information you have about the module (just delete the lines you don't know
anything about!) and write the Diz to the file.

The form looks like this

Filetype: [SQSH]-Protracker Module
Name:     Name Of The Module
Author:   Name Of The Author
(c) by:   The Copyright
Released: The Releasedate andor Party
Product': [Type]-Name Of The Production     ; or just leave [Type]- part out
Playtime: xx:yy, zz patts                   ; if you don't know the type of
Realsize: abc.def bytes                     ; the production!!!
Style:    Hardcore Trance                   ; type e.g: [Demo], [Intro] etc.
Comment:  Comment Line 1
          Comment Line 2
          Comment Line ...

Just remember you only have 44 characters per line!
DIZ-Ed only has 12 lines per file_id, but you can use as much as you want!

If you have any suggestions how to improve this standard, please contact
the author (See "Contact")... If you don't like this standard, you don't
have to use it, but you should, if you're using your own form, then please
send it to me.... I made this standard also that other programs can browse
the file and read the imformation (e.g. search for Author, but if one guy
writes composer, it can't be recognized, that's why!!!!

The Form file is in the same directory as the main file and this manual.
copy it just as the xDiz program itsself to your c: directory for use with
the scripts!!
@endnode

@node "FutureVersions" "Future Versions"
@prev "Standard"
@next "History"

Future Versions will have:
- a CLONE option for the filenames, so it will be possible to:

  xDiz MOD.xpkFile A CLONE
       which will mean
  xDiz MOD.xpkFile A MOD.xpkFile.xDiz

  or vice versa:

  xDiz CLONE A MOD.xpkFile.xDiz
       which will mean
  xDiz MOD.xpkFile A MOD.xpkFile.xDiz

    >>> Well, I now think that this isn't neccessary any more, <<<
 >>> as there are some BEAUTIFUL scripts included in this archive! <<<
         <<< OR WHAT DO YOU MEAN?? WRITE ME YOUR OPINION! >>>

- everything YOU would like to be implemented! So why not contact me?!!
@endnode

@node "History" "History"
@prev "FutureVersions"

  History... hmmm this CD suxx...


- Version 1.1 (Initial release)

  Well, the first release, date: somewhen in August after the Assembly '95.


- Version 1.4ß (24.8.1995)

  Implemented the IgnoreLines ("I") paramter for BBSes.. now you sysops can
  use it and have a better (shorter) filelisting... looks fuckin more cool
  and you got a better overview over the files (modules mainly!)
  Fixed some minor text bug (wrong text has was output!)
  Still some bugs in it I think (Dunno exactly, I have to check!), but this
  version should work...


- Version 1.5 (26.8.1995)

  Now the comment/date/time of the xpk-File remains when stripping/adding.
  Again fixed some minor text bugs. The known bug with the "I"-Parameter
  and the stripping of just the 1st line is correct.

@endnode
